ENTRY            A0350   20260323   20260508   20260508       A133
SUBENT        A0350001   20260323   20260508   20260508       A133
BIB                 11         51
TITLE      De-excitation of Ni-58,60,62 compound nuclei formed
           via symmetric and asymmetric entrance channels
AUTHOR     (E.Bozek,D.M.De Castro-Rizzo,S.Cavallaro,B.Delaunay,
           J.Delaunay,H.Dumont,A.D'onofrio,M.G.Saint-Laurent,
           L.Sperduto,F.Terrasi)
REFERENCE  (J,NP/A,451,171,1986)
           (J,NP/A,427,151,1984) - technical details, part data
           on figures.
           (T,DECASTRO-RIZZO,1983) - in French, thesis,
           Orsay-Paris XI University (1983). Tables, technical
           details
INSTITUTE  (2FR SAC)
FACILITY   (VDGT,2FR SAC)
INC-SOURCE Beams of 12C, 18O, 28Si and 30Si were produced by the
           9 MV Van de Graaff tandem accelerator. Typical beam
           current of ~ 80 nA were used at the lowest bombarding
           energies, and ~ 20 nA at higher energies.
           A typical running time was - 6 h.
DETECTOR   (GELI,HPGE) The gamma-rays were measured with two
           Ge(Li) and Ge(HP) detectors having efficiencies of
           22.3% and 23.9%, respectively, surrounded with a 10 cm
           lead shield. These detectors were located at 90. and
           55. degr. (or 125. degr. for some measurements) with
           respect to the beam axis, at a distance of 10-15 cm
           from the target, in order to minimize summing effects.
            The typical energy resolution was 2 keV FWHM for the
           1332 keV gamma-ray from a 60Co source.
           Photopeak efficiencies were determined by placing
           calibrated sources (152Eu, 56Co, 57Co, 182Ta and
           133Ba) at the target position.
ADD-RES    (COMP) Statistical model calculations.
METHOD     (BCINT) The reaction chamber 100 mm in diameter made
           out of 0.4 mm thick stainless steel was kept at a
           pressure of 10**(-6) Torr, in order to reduce carbon
           buildup on the target. The chamber was electrically
           insulated from the beam line and used as a Faraday cup.
           In the case of the 18O+44Ca reaction, another chamber,
           allowing the handling of the target under vacuum in
           order to avoid oxydation of the calcium, was used.
           (GSPEC)
REL-REF    (D,,J.M.Alexander+,J,ZP/A,307,149,1982)
           (D,,T.D.Thomas+,J,ARN,18,543,1968)
HISTORY    (19871012C)
           (20011012A) Several Subents were split according to
           EXFOR rules. Some reaction lines were corrected.
           Fusion and nonelastic data are added.
           (20020520U) Last checking has been done.
           (20260323A) SD: Corrections in all Subents.
           CRITIQUE deleted (Gamma-ray transitions were added to
           appropriated Subents. Full description is given in
           thesis).
ENDBIB              51
NOCOMMON             0          0
ENDSUBENT           54
SUBENT        A0350002   20260323   20260508   20260508       A133
BIB                  7         16
REACTION   (22-TI-46(6-C-12,X)27-CO-56,,SIG)
PART-DET   (G) Gamma transition used to determine residual cross
           section: 576. keV
SAMPLE     (22-TI-46,ENR=0.812) 46Ti evaporated onto 1 mm tantalum
           backing. Thickness of the 46Ta was 152 +- 12 ug/cm2
           and isotopic purity 81.2%.
CORRECTION The values of the effective cross sections have been
           corrected for the presence of the isotope 48Ti (14.5%)
           contained in the target of 46Ti.
ERR-ANALYS (DATA-ERR,10.,50.) An overall error of
             * 10-20% is for 1 mb < cross section < 50 mb.
             * 20-50% is for cross section < 1 mb.
           No any other information about source of uncertainty
